{"id":14881763,"mediaExerciseId":"2ef1fe97-04c9-47d6-884d-fffb45af5645","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"21","chapterTitle":"International Corporate Finance","groupId":612470,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":735,"solutions":[{"id":5978738,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to analyze the situation regarding exchange rate.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/fd9be9f0846eb63c0db5168e808725c1/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/fd9be9f0846eb63c0db5168e808725c1/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"An **Exchange Rate** is the value of a country's currency when *expressed in another country's currency.*\n\nExchange rate changes regularly due to various reasons which can either increase or decrease the value of one's currency.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/c8c0c5fac3bd3a0dd80c1f1382497281/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/c8c0c5fac3bd3a0dd80c1f1382497281/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"It is **good** to the company if the value of the currency it uses is **greater than** the value of the other country's currency. For example, the company is using U.S. dollars and the other country is using Japanese Yen. The company plans to sell and trade in Japan. \n\\\nTherefore, more Japanese Yen is required to purchase a dollar which means more income to the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/42b33bb382c2f8be1f7090c2e37eb503/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/42b33bb382c2f8be1f7090c2e37eb503/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"On the other hand, it is **bad** to the company if the value of the currency it uses is **less than** the value of the other country's currency. For example, the company is using U.S. dollars and the other country is using Japanese Yen. The company plans to buy in Japan.\n\\\nTherefore, more U.S. dollar is required to purchase a yen which means more loss to the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/5cf85470890f3b21c38e4f6d51b7000f/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/5cf85470890f3b21c38e4f6d51b7000f/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"As a conclusion, exchange rates can **either be good or bad** for the company depending on the value of the currency it uses is less than or greater than the value of the other country's currency it is making a transaction with.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":137,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/9bc6df0e6047b04fca4ee57547e0549a/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":69,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/8e69b72ab4e6f8f9471ba7f8b32a4eca/9bc6df0e6047b04fca4ee57547e0549a/lateximg.png","wi